    "narrative": "Today\u2019s roster construction for Ghost Ride the WHIP centers on exploiting high-ceiling matchups against weaker arms, with **Mickey Moniak** (75.98) and **Josh Naylor** (74.15) headlining our lineup. **Mickey Moniak** is our strongest play, bolstered by a significant +19% boost from facing Ryan Weiss\u2019s 7.36 xERA and a favorable order placement in the two-hole. Similarly, **Josh Naylor** remains a must-start despite facing Walker Buehler; the pitcher\u2019s struggling 5.19 xERA provides an ideal environment for **Josh Naylor** to deliver power production. While **Vinnie Pasquantino** (72.92) and **Tyler Soderstrom** (72.71) are also elite starts, we are keeping a close eye on **Jose Caballero**, whose 70.59 score is heavily driven by a +13% dynamic platoon edge against Suter, making him a sneaky source of production despite a lower-order spot.\n\nThe most difficult roster decision involved balancing the scarcity of stolen bases against our current floor requirements. **Kyle Karros** (50.20) narrowly made the cut; while his matchup against Ryan Weiss is highly favorable, his low-volume projection in a #8 hole makes him the most vulnerable member of the active roster should we need to shuffle for defensive substitutions. We are currently navigating several \"Lineup Pending\" designations\u2014specifically for **Luis Campusano**, **Max Muncy**, **Brice Turang**, **Mickey Moniak**, **Tyler Soderstrom**, and **Josh Naylor**\u2014where our analysis assumes historical batting positions. If these players slide further down their respective lineups, those efficiency scores will compress, potentially necessitating a pivot to bench depth. We remain anchored by our core, though we are monitoring weather flags that could impact the high-ceiling outings projected for **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** and **Giancarlo Stanton**, both of whom benefit from positive wind conditions today.",
